5.1 Setting the BibTeX Dialect
==============================

BibLaTeX files use the same `.bib' suffix that BibTeX files use.
Whether a file is interpreted as a BibTeX or a BibLaTeX is determined by
the user option “Bibtex Dialect” (i.e., the variable
`ebib-bibtex-dialect'). Possible values for this option are `BibTeX'
and `biblatex'. (These values are taken from the variable
`bibtex-dialect-list'.) The default value of this option is `BibTeX'.
If you wish to read or create BibLaTeX files in Ebib, you'll need to
change the value of `ebib-bibtex-dialect'.

   The dialect specified determines which entry types Ebib recognises
and which fields it expects. Reading a file with the wrong dialect
setting will most likely result in a series of “Illegal entry type”
errors.  Note, however, that these entries will still be loaded and
displayed, but they will be highlighted with Emacs' `error' face.
Fields that are not defined for the current dialect are displayed as
undefined fields (i.e., below all other fields in the entry buffer).

   The option “Bibtex Dialect” sets the default dialect. It is possible
to set the dialect for individual files as well. To do this, load the
file and then set the dialect through the menu option «Ebib | BibTeX
Dialect» or with the command `M-x ebib-set-dialect'. You only need to do
this once for a file, because the setting is saved in the `.bib' file
in the local variable block. (If no local variable block exists, one is
created.) The setting is actually saved as a file-local value for the
variable `bibtex-dialect', which means that if you should open the file
directly in `bibtex-mode', Emacs will apply the dialect setting as
well. (Note, by the way, that Ebib's option to set the BibTeX Dialect
is different from the one provided by `bibtex-mode'.  Specifically, the
former uses the variable `ebib-bibtex-dialect', while the latter uses
`bibtex-dialect'.)

   The mode line of the index buffer shows the dialect that Ebib assumes
for the current database. Note that this does not necessarily mean that
the dialect is set in the `.bib' file: if the file does not have a
dialect setting, the mode line shows the default setting.


